# 0.4 MONETARY POLICY WITH ABUNDANTRESERVES  

To introduce the roles of the [Federal Reserve system](../Chapter%2012/Fed%20Fund%20Futures.md) or "[the Fed](.md)" as a modern central bank, Table O.4 shows its pre-crisis balance sheet, as of December 2007. One role, the creation and maintenance of a widely accepted national [currency](../../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forwards%20and%20Futures%20Notes.md), is achieved by purchasing government bonds with that [currency](../../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forwards%20and%20Futures%20Notes.md). The [currency](../../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forwards%20and%20Futures%20Notes.md) of the United States is comprised of green bills labeled as liabilities of the Federal Reserve, that is, as "Federal Reserve Notes." In terms of the balance sheet, therefore, outstanding [currency](../../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forwards%20and%20Futures%20Notes.md) is a liability and [Treasury securities](US%20Markets.md) are assets. Put another way, [currency](../../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forwards%20and%20Futures%20Notes.md) is "backed" by government bonds. As shown in the table, $\$773.9$ billion of currency outstanding was about $83\%$ of Federal Reserve liabilities.  

