A second role of the central bank is to provide [liquidity](../../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md) to banks under short-term distress. As mentioned earlier, bank assets, like loans, are relatively illiquid, while bank liabilities, like deposits or short-term borrowings. from other [financial institutions](../../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions%20Lecture%20Notes.md), may be due immediately. Therefore, a bank. may find itself solvent but illiquid, that is, with assets of sufficient value to pay off its liabilities but without enough cash on hand to meet its immediate obligations. In these situations, a bank can borrow from [the Fed](.md) through the [discount window](.md) on any acceptable collateral. The [discount window](.md). borrowings of a well-managed bank are expected to be infrequent and of relatively limited [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md).  

The third role discussed here, as set out in the Federal Reserve Act, is to "maintain long run growth of the monetary and credit aggregates...so as to promote effectively the goals of maximum employment, stable prices, and moderate [long-term interest rates](../../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%208-%20Markets,%20Meltdowns,%20and%20Arbitrage/The%20Economist%20Margin%20Call%20of%20the%20Wild.md)." Despite the three objectives, by the way, [the Fed](.md) is often said to have a "dual mandate" of full employment and low [inflation](../../../International%20Finance/Bridgewater/Principles%20For%20Navigating%20Big%20Debt%20Cycles/Part%20II%20Detailed%20Case%20Studies/German%20Debt%20Crisis%20andHyperinflation%20(1918–1924)/War%20Economies%20and%20Hyperinflation.md). In any case, two points are made before proceeding:  

1. To ensure that banks have the resources to honor all requests to withdraw deposits that they are likely to receive, banks have been required to maintain cash and reserves, which are deposits held at a Federal Reserve bank. Until 2008, banks did not earn interest on their reserve balances.18   
2. [The Fed](.md) sets the total amount of reserves in the [banking system](../../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/II.%20The%20Roles%20of%20Banks%20and%20Derivative%20Markets%20in%20Resolving%20Problems%20Inherent%20in%20Debt%20Contracts/Class%203-%20Financial%20Intermediation%20and%20Delegated%20Loan%20Monitoring%20,%20Intro%20to%20Bankruptcy%20and%20Debt%20Restructuring/Class%20Slide%203%20Financial%20Intermediation%20and%20Delegated%20Monitoring.md). To add to reserves, [the Fed](.md) might buy a Treasury bond from a bank. The bank's account at its Federal Reserve Bank is credited with the purchase  

price -- which increases bank reserves and the liabilities of [the Fed](.md) - and. the Treasury bond is added to the assets of [the Fed](.md). [The Fed](.md) can also add to reserves by lending money to a bank through a repurchase agreement or repo.19 The money is credited to the bank's account at [the Fed](.md), which is a reserve liability of [the Fed](.md), and the loan obligation is added. to [the Fed](.md)'s assets. To reduce reserves, [the Fed](.md) can do the opposite of. these two transactions, that is, sell a bond to a bank or borrow money from a bank through a repo. In light of this discussion, the quantity of Treasury assets and net repo assets on [the Fed](.md)'s balance sheet enter into the determination of the total amount of reserves in the [banking system](../../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/II.%20The%20Roles%20of%20Banks%20and%20Derivative%20Markets%20in%20Resolving%20Problems%20Inherent%20in%20Debt%20Contracts/Class%203-%20Financial%20Intermediation%20and%20Delegated%20Loan%20Monitoring%20,%20Intro%20to%20Bankruptcy%20and%20Debt%20Restructuring/Class%20Slide%203%20Financial%20Intermediation%20and%20Delegated%20Monitoring.md).  

Before the [financial crisis](../../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%209-%20Bailouts%20and%20Bank%20Failures/Squam%20Lake%20Group%20Letter.md) of 2007-2009, reserves were scarce in the sense that banks traded reserves among themselves in the interbank [fed funds](../Chapter%2012/Fed%20Fund%20Futures.md) market. Banks that needed reserves to satisfy their reserve requirements borrowed [fed funds](../Chapter%2012/Fed%20Fund%20Futures.md), while banks that had excess reserves, on which they did not earn interest, loaned [fed funds](../Chapter%2012/Fed%20Fund%20Futures.md) at the market-determined [fed funds](../Chapter%2012/Fed%20Fund%20Futures.md) rate. In this setting, if [the Fed](.md) wanted to ease monetary conditions, to stimulate the economy (i.e., growth was too low and [inflation](../../../International%20Finance/Bridgewater/Principles%20For%20Navigating%20Big%20Debt%20Cycles/Part%20II%20Detailed%20Case%20Studies/German%20Debt%20Crisis%20andHyperinflation%20(1918–1924)/War%20Economies%20and%20Hyperinflation.md) not a threat), it would add reserves to the [banking system](../../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/II.%20The%20Roles%20of%20Banks%20and%20Derivative%20Markets%20in%20Resolving%20Problems%20Inherent%20in%20Debt%20Contracts/Class%203-%20Financial%20Intermediation%20and%20Delegated%20Loan%20Monitoring%20,%20Intro%20to%20Bankruptcy%20and%20Debt%20Restructuring/Class%20Slide%203%20Financial%20Intermediation%20and%20Delegated%20Monitoring.md), which - by increasing supply relative to demand in the market for reserves - would decrease [the fed](.md) funds rate and likely increase the volume of bank loans to commercial enterprises. Similarly, if [the Fed](.md) wanted to tighten monetary conditions, to slow the economy (e.g., growth was too inflationary), it would remove reserves from the system, which would increase [the fed](.md) funds rate and likely decrease bank loans to commercial enterprises. Finally, the means by which [the Fed](.md) changed reserves were called open market operations and consisted almost exclusively. of lending and borrowing money through [repurchase agreements](../../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%207-%20CP,%20Repo,%20and%20the%20Crisis/Class%20Slides%20On%20Repurchase%20Agreements.md).  

In response to the [financial crisis](../../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%209-%20Bailouts%20and%20Bank%20Failures/Squam%20Lake%20Group%20Letter.md) and ensuing [Great Recession](../../../Advanced%20Financial%20Analysis%20and%20Valuation/Problem%20Sets/HKS%20The%20Banking%20Industry.md), [the Fed](.md) tried to stimulate the economy as just described, by reducing [the fed](.md) funds rate from $5.25\%$ in September 2007 to a range of between. $0\%$ and $0.25\%$ by December 2008. But having reduced [interest rates](../Chapter%202/Interest%20Rate%20Quotations.md) to nearly zero and wanting to stimulate the economy even more forcefully, [the Fed](.md) began what became known as [quantitative easing](Negative%20Rates%20and%20Qe%20in%20Europe%20and%20Japan.md) $(\mathcal{Q}E)$ : it purchased great quantities of US [Treasury securities](US%20Markets.md) and "[agency MBS](../Chapter%2015/The%20Mortgage%20Market%20in%20the%20United%20States.md)," which are MBS issued by government agencies and GSEs. At the start of the program, purchases of MBS directly eased stresses arising from the overleveraged positions in mortgages and mortgage products that were at the heart of the crisis. Experts do not agree, however, on the mechanism by which the subsequent massive purchases of both Treasuries and MBS were to stimulate the economy, although  

possibilities include lowering intermediate- and [long-term interest rates](../../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%208-%20Markets,%20Meltdowns,%20and%20Arbitrage/The%20Economist%20Margin%20Call%20of%20the%20Wild.md).   
(rather than just [the fed](.md) funds rate); pushing investors out of relatively safe.   
Treasuries and [agency MBS](../Chapter%2015/The%20Mortgage%20Market%20in%20the%20United%20States.md) and into riskier products like corporate bonds.   
and loans; and flooding banks with reserves. In fact, the chairman of the.   
Fed at the time said a few years later that "the problem with QE is that it works in practice, but it doesn't work in theory."20.  

Figure O.13 shows the composition of the asset side of [the Fed](.md)'s balance. sheet from June 2006 to June 2021. Note that the total of Fed assets is often referred to by market participants simply as [the Fed](.md)'s "balance sheet." In any case, during the [financial crisis](../../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%209-%20Bailouts%20and%20Bank%20Failures/Squam%20Lake%20Group%20Letter.md) itself, from 2007 to 2009, assets were elevated by expanded repo lending, lending through the [discount window](.md),. loans through emergency facilities that [the Fed](.md) put in place at the time, and through swap lines, through which [the Fed](.md) lends US dollars to foreign central banks, collateralized by foreign [currency](../../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forwards%20and%20Futures%20Notes.md). While small in hindsight, this bal-. ance sheet expansion before QE was unprecedented, increasing from about $\$900$ billion at the start of 2007 to over. $\$2$ trillion by the end of 2008.. From then, [the Fed](.md) fully engaged in QE by purchasing Treasuries and [agency MBS](../Chapter%2015/The%20Mortgage%20Market%20in%20the%20United%20States.md), and the balance sheet grew dramatically. By the end of 2014, however, [the Fed](.md) decided that [economic conditions](../../../International%20Finance/Bridgewater/Chapters/US%20Debt%20Crisis%20and%20Adjustment%20(2007–2011).md) had improved enough to discontinue further stimulus. It stopped buying new assets, though it continued to. roll over principal repayments from its holdings. From December 2015 to summer 2019, it raised the target [Fed funds](../Chapter%2012/Fed%20Fund%20Futures.md) rate from a range of $0\%$ to $0.25\%$ to a range of $2.25\%$ to $2.50\%$ and, in what was named the "normalization" of the balance sheet, began allowing assets to decline with principal repayments. [The Fed](.md) was clear to point out, however, that the balance sheet would not decline to anywhere near its size before the [financial crisis](../../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%209-%20Bailouts%20and%20Bank%20Failures/Squam%20Lake%20Group%20Letter.md), because, as explained later, post-crisis [monetary policy](../../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%209-%20Bailouts%20and%20Bank%20Failures/Articles/The%20Economist%20Regime%20Change.md) requires greater levels of reserves. Along these lines, in summer 2019, [the Fed](.md) resumed the reinvestment of principal payments to maintain the size of the balance sheet. Then, in response to turmoil in the repo market in September 2019, further described later, [the Fed](.md) started growing the balance sheet again. [The Fed](.md) also judged that "implications of global developments for the economic outlook as well as muted [inflation](../../../International%20Finance/Bridgewater/Principles%20For%20Navigating%20Big%20Debt%20Cycles/Part%20II%20Detailed%20Case%20Studies/German%20Debt%20Crisis%20andHyperinflation%20(1918–1924)/War%20Economies%20and%20Hyperinflation.md) pressures" warranted lowering rates and reduced [the Fed](.md) funds target range to $1.50\%$ to $1.75\%$ by November 2019. Finally, with the onset of the COvID pandemic and economic shutdowns, [the Fed](.md) reduced rates back to the range of between $0\%$ and $0.25\%$ and aggressively bought Treasuries and MBs. As of June 2021, [the Fed](.md)'s balance sheet stood at $\$8.25$ trillion, more than nine times its size before the [financial crisis](../../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%209-%20Bailouts%20and%20Bank%20Failures/Squam%20Lake%20Group%20Letter.md).  

